data.title: Every road in Coventry where street lights are being turned off overnight
data.meta_description: Coventry council's new policy will impact over 2,500 streets in the city
data.text:
Over 2,500 roads in Coventry now have no street lights on for hours at night. It comes amid a public outcry over the new council "part-night" lighting scheme.

The move involves turning off street lamps from midnight to 5.30am every day except on Fridays and Saturdays, when it happens an hour later. Councillors backed the policy in February and since mid-July it has been in place across the city.

Overall 2539 city streets are being left in the dark for at least four hours overnight, according to a council list. We broke this down by each of the 18 council areas and found some have more roads affected than others.

READ MORE:

Residents demand street lights are turned back on as cost-cutting measures branded 'dangerous'

Anger grows over streetlights being turned off as readers say it's like 'the dark ages'

A full list of the streets affected can be found below. The council says the change will save it £700,000 in energy costs per year, and also cut carbon emissions and light pollution.

But at the time of writing, 30 July, more than 1,000 people have signed a petition demanding the council bring back nightly street lights. Some city residents branded the switch-off "dangerous" and say they feel unsafe.

A council spokesperson said it has not seen a rise in crime on streets with part-night lighting and added that busier streets and junctions, controlled crossings and public footpaths away from roads are not being affected.
